        {
            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Gallery Label",
            "textentryhtml":"Okada Beisanjin was the son of a rice merchant in Osaka and continued in his family’s profession; this may be the basis for his artist-name, Beisanjin (literally “rice mountain man”). He was one of the major <em>bunjinga</em>, literati-style painters who appropriated Chinese elements while developing their own personal styles. Beisanjin closely studied illustrated books of Chinese paintings and came to excel in landscape&nbsp; compositions. This painting typifies his style with its economy of brushstrokes used to create an original and serene image.",
